long_desc.thetext:
Register a simple event handler like the following for the "keydown" event:

_handleKeydown : function(ev) {
  alert("keydown event");
}

Now press any key, the alert shows up. Close the alert, and press that very same key again. The event will not be fired! Press that key a third time, and the alert shows up.

You can also press other keys in between, that does not change a thing. For example, press 
a  -> alert
b  -> alert
x  -> alert
a  -> nothing....
b  -> alert
a  -> alert (here it comes!)

I guess that when using alert() or confirm(), Firefox fires no keyup event. 
Don't know how to fix that though, perhaps add a method to the KeyEventHandler like clearEvent(keyIdentifier) to manually invoke after an alert. Or globally replace window.alert() and window.confirm() by a custom function that delegates to the original saved function and resets the KeyEventHandler afterwards. However this might be dangerous and could lead to unwanted side effects.

.... KeyEventHandler
construct : function() {
  ... original code
  this.__origAlertFunc = window.alert;
  this.__origConfirmFunc = window.confirm;
  window.alert = function(msg) {
    this.__origAlertFunc.call(window, msg);
    this.__resetKeyEvents(); // or whatever it does
  };
  window.confirm = function(msg) {
    this.__origConfirmFunc.call(window, msg);
    this.__resetKeyEvents(); // or whatever it does
  };
}


